Another shoe has dropped in the long-running, multigenerational drama of th=
e Lauder family. Last week, The Wall Street Journal reported that first cou=
sins William and Jane are feuding, Exhibit A being a letter Jane sent to ce=
rtain members of the Est=C3=A9e Lauder board blaming William, the chairman,=
 for =E2=80=9Cdestroying the company.=E2=80=9D We=E2=80=99ve all heard abou=
t the rumored dissension within the family=E2=80=93=E2=80=93from how the co=
mpany should be run, to who should run it, to where its brands should be so=
ld (Amazon is working out well, by the way)=E2=80=93=E2=80=93but it=E2=80=
=99s rare that the inner machinery of America=E2=80=99s most storied beauty=
 dynasty is exposed for all to see, and by a member of the family, no less.=
 It=E2=80=99s not pretty.

The proximate cause of the rift was the elevation of St=C3=A9phane de La Fa=
verie to
C.E.O., replacing the outgoing Fabrizio Freda. It was a job that Jane herse=
lf very much coveted and, as both a family member and the company=E2=80=99s=
 chief data officer and executive vice president of enterprise marketing, p=
erhaps regarded as her birthright. When Jane learned that de La Faverie was=
 to be anointed=E2=80=94before the news was made public=E2=80=94she resigne=
d. Around the same time, William, whom Jane blamed for enabling Freda=E2=80=
=99s long and recently unprofitable tenure, announced he=E2=80=99d be stepp=
ing down as executive chairman. Of course, there were nuances here, too: Ja=
ne was presumably also pissed that William=E2=80=99s support of Freda had c=
ome at the expense of her own elevation. Also, William=E2=80=99s demotion w=
as ostensibly prompted by the board. After all, ELC has endured nine consec=
utive unprofitable quarters. (A spokesperson for The Est=C3=A9e Lauder Comp=
anies declined to comment.)

Yes, it=E2=80=99s messy, and yes, Est=C3=A9e=E2=80=99s grandkids sound like
petulant grown children, and ones who could never contemplate an existence =
outside the confines of the GM building. But Jane is probably the only fami=
ly member who=E2=80=99s meaningfully challenged the way ELC operates, and s=
he=E2=80=99s a more formidable opponent than anyone realized. =E2=80=9CIt l=
ooks like Jane has some balls,=E2=80=9D said a person with ties to the fami=
ly. =E2=80=9CShe doesn=E2=80=99t feel that the board has acted as it should=
 have, and William was the executive chairman and said yes, yes, yes to Fab=
rizio time and again.=E2=80=9D

Freda, unfairly or not, has been shouldering much of the blame for the comp=
any=E2=80=99s market cap freefall. He=E2=80=99s been C.E.O. since 2008, and=
 for many of those years, things were very good. The Lauder family, as aver=
se to leadership change as most wealthy families, was hoping that the same =
executive would be able to turn things around, even after it became clear h=
e couldn=E2=80=99t. William, one of several family members with outsize
influence on the board, was likely in favor of de La Faverie=E2=80=99s prom=
otion, much to Jane=E2=80=99s chagrin.

On some level, perhaps, none of this is entirely surprising. William, 64, w=
as the C.E.O. before Freda=E2=80=94until the board forced him to step down =
in 2008 while he was still in his 40s. (The board created the executive cha=
irman role for him as a consolation prize.) Sixteen years later, some of th=
e very same board members again took away William=E2=80=99s role. Alas, any=
 efforts the family had made to =E2=80=9Ctake the heat off William=E2=80=9D=
 and protect him from being tainted by the current mess, according to a sou=
rce who knows the family, appear to have been in vain.

