The Leak

Jane=E2=80=99s letter was clearly a sort of theatrical artifact, enabling h=
er to distance herself from corporate ineptitude, nuke a family member, and=
 put the board on notice while possibly courting the fealty of shareholders=
=2E The question of who leaked her mani=
festo to the Journal is less clear. On=
e theory is that it was Jane=E2=80=99s own team, with the intention to push=
 the board to name her as executive chairperson. The thinking goes that Jan=
e surely knew anything she put in writing could eventually be made public.

A former executive dismissed this scenario. =E2=80=9CIf it was her, we woul=
d have been hearing rumblings 10 years ago,=E2=80=9D this person said. =E2=
=80=9CNobody waits 30 years, and only when they get to wit=E2=80=99s end, a=
nd the ultimate humiliation, do they preempt and quit=E2=80=93=E2=80=93on t=
he heels of having done nothing for decades that would ever
be called into question, and never having been a source. It=E2=80=99s not h=
er nature.=E2=80=9D (A source close to Jane told me that Jane =E2=80=9Cdefi=
nitively didn=E2=80=99t leak it.=E2=80=9D) The Chapin and Stanford grad has=
 always been introverted and cautious, much less visible socially and acros=
s the brand than her sister, Aerin.

Jane=E2=80=99s 80-year-old father, Ronald=E2=80=94the prolific art collecto=
r, onetime mayoral candidate, and deep-pocketed Republican donor=E2=80=94co=
uld have had the motivation to stir things up. He=E2=80=99s presumably upse=
t that his daughter was passed over while his nephew William cooled his hee=
ls. And Ronald, I=E2=80=99m told by several sources, has used the media to =
his advantage in the past.

A more apposite question may be: Whose reputation remains intact after the =
Journal=E2=80=99s report? =E2=80=9CThe fact that St=C3=A9phane wasn=E2=80=
=99t painted in a negative light is telling,=E2=80=9D mused an analyst from=
 a top bank. Another source noted that an article about the family=E2=80=99=
s
internecine squabbles certainly validates the board=E2=80=99s decision to g=
o outside the family for the company=E2=80=99s next chief executive.

