          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Another shoe has dr=
opped in the long-running, multigenerational drama of the <b>Lauder </b>fam=
ily. Last week, <i>The</i> <i>Wall Street Journal</i> reported that first c=
ousins <b>William</b> and <b>Jane</b> are feuding, Exhibit A being a letter=
 Jane sent to certain members of the Est=C3=A9e Lauder board blaming Willia=
m, the chairman, for =E2=80=9Cdestroying the company.=E2=80=9D We=E2=80=99v=
e all heard about the rumored dissension within the family=E2=80=93=E2=80=
=93from how the company <i>should</i> be run, to <i>who</i> should run it, =
to <i>where</i> its brands should be sold (Amazon is working out well, by t=
he way)=E2=80=93=E2=80=93but it=E2=80=99s rare that the inner machinery of =
America=E2=80=99s most storied beauty dynasty is exposed for all to see, an=
d by a member of the family, no less. It=E2=80=99s not pretty.<br/><br/>The=
 proximate cause of the rift was the elevation of<b> St=C3=A9phane de La Fa=
verie</b> to
C.E.O., replacing the outgoing <b>Fabrizio Freda</b>. It was a job that Jan=
e herself very much coveted and, as both a family member <i>and</i> the com=
pany=E2=80=99s chief data officer and executive vice president of enterpris=
e marketing, perhaps regarded as her birthright. When Jane learned that de =
La Faverie was to be anointed=E2=80=94before the news was made public=E2=80=
=94she resigned. Around the same time, William, whom Jane blamed for enabli=
ng Freda=E2=80=99s long and recently unprofitable tenure, announced he=E2=
=80=99d be stepping down as executive chairman. Of course, there were nuanc=
es here, too: Jane was presumably also pissed that William=E2=80=99s suppor=
t of Freda had come at the expense of her own elevation. Also, William=E2=
=80=99s demotion was ostensibly prompted by the board. After all, ELC has e=
ndured nine consecutive unprofitable quarters. (A spokesperson for The Est=
=C3=A9e Lauder Companies declined to comment.)<br/><br/><i>Yes</i>, it=E2=
=80=99s messy, and <i>yes</i>, <b>Est=C3=A9e</b>=E2=80=99s grandkids sound =
like
petulant grown children, and ones who could <i>never </i>contemplate an exi=
stence outside the confines of the GM building. But Jane is probably the <i=
>only </i>family member who=E2=80=99s meaningfully challenged the way ELC o=
perates, and she=E2=80=99s a more formidable opponent than anyone realized.=
 =E2=80=9CIt looks like Jane has some balls,=E2=80=9D said a person with ti=
es to the family. =E2=80=9CShe doesn=E2=80=99t feel that the board has acte=
d as it should have, and William was the executive chairman and said <i>yes=
</i>, <i>yes</i>, <i>yes</i> to Fabrizio time and again.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>=
Freda, unfairly or not, has been shouldering much of the blame for the comp=
any=E2=80=99s market cap freefall. He=E2=80=99s been C.E.O. since 2008, and=
 for many of those years, things were very good. The Lauder family, as aver=
se to leadership change as most wealthy families, was hoping that the same =
executive would be able to turn things around, even after it became clear h=
e couldn=E2=80=99t. William, one of several family members with outsize
influence on the board, was likely in favor of de La Faverie=E2=80=99s prom=
otion, much to Jane=E2=80=99s chagrin. <br/><br/>On some level, perhaps, no=
ne of this is entirely surprising. William, 64, was the C.E.O. before Freda=
=E2=80=94until the board forced <i>him</i> to step down in 2008 while he wa=
s still in his 40s. (The board created the executive chairman role for him =
as a consolation prize.) Sixteen years later, some of the very same board m=
embers <i>again</i> took away William=E2=80=99s role. Alas, any efforts the=
 family had made to =E2=80=9Ctake the heat off William=E2=80=9D and protect=
 him from being tainted by the current mess, according to a source who know=
s the family, appear to have been in vain.<br/></td>
         </tr>
